<br>
So find yerself a nice nuetral character (rogues by their nature and abilities tend to veiw the world pragmaticaly) and arrange a transfer of the item. There are also some very good IC ways to view this and incorporate it (use your imagination). <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ueliezeroferudin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Eliezer of Erudin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 753<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/28/02 1:44:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2204.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Is Evils trading with Goods hypocritical?</span><hr size=1> Cylria,<br>
<br>
I understand and agree with that point.  My point was really more directed to the POV that said &quot;You may be selling to me OOC but for me it is still IC&quot;  So if I'm like Count Evil, and they are like Granny Goodness, and I sell them a Happy Love Bracer, they'd be all like &quot;Count Evil isn't so evil after all, he's just a big sweetie.&quot;<br>
<br>
That's just dumb :-p<br>
<br>
I agree with your points about there being a difference between IC Knowledge and OOC Knowledge - BUT, as many others have pointed out, without a DM/GM to tell you which is which it is impossible to set a 'standard.'  Maybe everyone DOES know what an item is and who can use it by simple examination - There isn't anything in the game to suggest otherwise.<br>
<br>
I'm all for people playing as they see fit, but at least let's be honest with ourselves. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ubraellarth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Braellarth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 115<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/29/02 7:12:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2204.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Bah</span><hr size=1> Most items in EQ have a limited graphic... and hence there name is actually there description.<br>
<br>
There are some wepons that are different this and armor.<br>
<br>
Take for a few examples:<br>
<br>
Langseax/seax - wasnt an seax a daggar and langseax was a refference obviously long-daggar.. it's a two handed sword just that they used a generic sword to represent it.<br>
<br>
Bloodmoon - a curved blade, a one handed sythe really... moon refering to a blade almost sickle like, sounds a nasty piece of work to me. And ended up with a sythe model like the ones in the warrens.<br>
<br>
For a start how would you know what certain items are and dont go about the who would use thing... take some shadowknight armor for instance.<br>
Dark forge, Umbral, Bloodember, Dark runed... all are dark shades and colors or have a reference to there makeing.<br>
Bloodember - dark red the color of blood, ember i presume is a reference to it's forging... i mean if you run upto a pair of greaves that looked like they mixed baked blood into the finish and metalwork... would you even pick them up let alone try to sell them... who the heck do you think would be buying them in the first place! yuk.<br>
<br>
And if you saw that armor you think you wouldnt tell anyone... down the bar with all your friends and it comes up in conversation.. or the bards have not heard of it.. if i play a shadowknight i make it an effort to know both the holy items of my deity as well as oposed deitys.<br>
<br>
And personally i cannot destroy items even if they were for a good race, there are people behind there characters and it will probably give them much more fun than i get out of destroying it and saying &quot;ahh another foul paladin blade smelted to make dairy spoons what a profitable day&quot;.<br>
